value.0: "Are we ready then?" Jaboli's spirit purrs quietly, waiting patiently to find out her ultimate fate.
Jaboli's spirit rises up, trembling with either fear or rage. She appears to listen to an inaudible voice, and then looks at you carefully.
"This is not a test I envy you, my friend. Still, I would rather be alive than dead. I assume that the voice speaking to me also spoke to you. So what shall you do?"
"Will you choose the path of wisdom and discernment and choose me for an ally? Oh, what a typically rakshasa thing to say. Sorry, I didn't mean it that way."
"That would be the wisest choice. I hope you shall return, friend."
"And what did your best wisdom and judgment decide?"
"Then I shall wait patiently until you are ready. It would not be wise to choose quickly."

LinkComment.value: spirit fades away, no death scream

value.0: Jaboli's eyes widen and she lets out a ferocious howl before her spirit loses its substance and fades away.
She sighs and nods. "I cannot say this is entirely unexpected. Good luck, friend." Her spirit fades away into the darkness.

LinkComment.value: Spirit form disappears, body gets up from the ground, a fully healed, level one fighter.

value.0: "I think your judgment is perfectly sound, and you followed it. Things shall be well."
"You have made a good choice; one I will give you no reason to regret."
"We know much about each other, yet we have often kept secrets too. I will answer as best as I can."
"Then perhaps you are ready to choose, unless you wish to seek answers from the others first? Either way, I am not going anywhere until you are ready."
"While I feel for the difficulties she has faced, I do not care for Kaidala overmuch. She is too insecure, which goes against my own confident nature."
"Calibast is strong, and a good companion, so I would recommend him on those counts. Trip is rather pathetic in a fight, but he is an excellent thief."
"You know your strengths and weaknesses better than I, and the decision is yours. If you desperately need a healer, then you might need the insecure nymph. I just hope you will choose me."
"I can only ever offer an opinion, but I will always tell you the truth. I will not hide behind a false mask just to say pleasing things."
"The damage to her physical body was bad enough, but her spirit was far worse off. She will do as you ask, but she will accept death better than any."
"The rest of us will fight to hold on to life, but I worry that Kaidala will suddenly give in one day and let herself die when she is really needed."
"Trip is weak and cowardly, but I think he could be trained to be useful. When he strikes from the shadows, he can be quite formidable."
"Magic, intelligence, a knowledge of tactics, and an ability to discern the motivations and lies of others. If I am in your party, I will try to be sure that no one deceives you."
"All of these abilities wrapped up in a perfectly magnificent package... how could you resist?"
"The power of the rakshasa is well known, though I am far limited in comparison to how I was before banishment. My people stripped me of my sorcererous powers, forcing me to learn something new."
"I am now a wizard, and I find my new calling to be more to my liking. I also still retain some of my natural spell resistance, despite the weakness of my exile."
Jaboli nods slowly. "I am good at analyzing people and what they say, so that I can determine what motivates them, and often I can tell if they are lying. This could be useful to you."
"I was always smarter than most of my peers. I find the intellectual challenge of wizardry to be more in line with my own nature. So, yes, I am good at it."
"I am also good at analyzing people and what they say, so that I can determine what motivates them, and often I can tell if they are lying. This could be useful to you."
"I have a different view on life than my people do. I would rather not discuss the details of my exile right now. I have other qualities though."
"I am good at analyzing people and what they say. I can determine what motivates them, and often I can tell if they are lying. This could be useful to you."

"Not at all. It is just that such a statement would be very egotistical and very typical for one of my species. As you already know, I have a rather different view on life then the rest of my species."
"You are a scholar of the arcane arts, as am I. While I have greatly enjoyed our time together and the things we have learned and shared, I find it highly unlikely that you would choose me."
"Besides, such a statement would be very egotistical and very typical for one of my species. As you already know, I have a rather different view on life than the rest of my species."
"As you wish. What would you like to discuss, friend?"
"Such a callous attitude; are you afraid that you might learn something? Or are you so intimidated by my powerful, female, feline confidence that you forget how to behave in civilized conversation?"
"Never mind, my... friend, I am sure you have your own goals in this conversation, so steer it towards a topic more to your liking."

"Rakshasa believe that they are so superior to all other races that they have the right to do whatever they want. We enslave entire races, wiping out civilizations to further our own selfish designs."

"I look at my people and I see a power and nobility eclipsed by foolish strife and selfish cruelty. If we could only turn from our corruption and focus on a just society, great things could be accomplished."
Jaboli grins wildly at you. "Enough of the philosophical discussions though; let us go back to our usual banter. Have you made a decision yet?"
"I do not claim that we should all run out and give everything we own to the weaker races, or such nonsense."
"I simply think that we should uphold a common set of laws that all people should obey. Nobles should not be exempt from these laws, nor the rich."
Jaboli frowns and growls, "And it did so to my fellow rakshasa, but I do not wish to speak of that. Tell me, have you decided upon my fate yet?"
"No, I do not believe that anyone is above justice. That is why I will understand if you do not chose me."
"Not for good; for justice! Killing someone might not be a good thing, but it can be a just thing."
"I need to speak to the others before I decide."
"I have made a choice."
"I've changed my mind. I am not ready to choose yet."
"I judge you unfit to live. Goodbye."
"I cannot choose you, sorry."

value.0: "Against my better judgment, I think I will need your skills."
"I would like you to return to help me."

value.0: "I have a few questions for you first."
"That is all my questions."
"What do you think about the others?"
"I have other questions."
"Thanks for your opinion."
"How badly could her insecurity be a problem?"
"What skills can you offer me, exactly?"
"Tell me why I should choose you."
"I haven't heard anything to make me think you are worth saving yet."
"Are you a good wizard?"
"Anything else useful?"
"Why were you exiled?"
"You mean I shouldn't choose you?"
"Let's talk about something else."
"I couldn't care less about your view on life."
"And what are your views?"
"Sounds good to me."
"What is a just society?"
"Sounds like a noble ideal."
"Sounds very unrealistic."
"Sounds stupid to me."
"So you are one of those holier-than-thou types?"
"So you see yourself as a force for good?"
